                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d402">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/4–1846: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Mukden</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Clubb</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Mukden</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1946-04-18T14:00:00+08:00"
                            >April 18, 1946—2 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received April 19—9:13 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>38. French newsman who witnessed take over Fushun by Chinese (ReConstel 31, April
                    17, noon) states the whole combine tin subsidiary enterprises was involved in
                    action and that in effect Chinese took over from Soviet personnel by force. This
                    is confirmed by Soviet newsman who states that action was taken while Chungking
                    negotiations (Constel April 9, 9 a.m.<note n="16" xml:id="d402fn16">Not
                        printed.</note>) were still in train.</p>
                <pb facs="0793" n="781" xml:id="pg_781"/>
                <p>Please repeat Chungking, Shanghai.</p>
                <p>This Chinese action will, of course, constitute element of some importance for
                    current Sino-Soviet relations.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Clubb</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
